{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16830"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.3,0.3,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9521"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9521"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62153"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10317"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22493"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents with central cord syndrome following trauma. Magnetic resonance imaging shows a lesion at the second thoracic (T2) vertebral level involving the anterior horn cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the distribution of lower motor neuron signs in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T2 level only","All levels below T2","T2 and all levels below","All levels below T2 except sacral region","Sacral region only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen anterior horn cells are damaged, \u003Cstrong\u003Elower motor neuron signs occur only at the level of injury (T2)\u003C/strong\u003E. This is because anterior horn cells are the lower motor neurons that directly innervate skeletal muscles at their segmental level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll levels below T2\u003C/strong\u003E - Lower levels maintain intact anterior horn cells; any weakness below the lesion would be upper motor neuron in nature\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET2 and all levels below\u003C/strong\u003E - Only the segments at T2 would show lower motor neuron signs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll levels below T2 except sacral region\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no anatomical basis for sparing the sacral region\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacral region only\u003C/strong\u003E - The sacral region is not specifically affected by a T2 lesion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELower motor neuron signs include flaccid paralysis, muscle wasting, fasciculations, and decreased reflexes. These signs only appear in muscles innervated by the damaged anterior horn cells at T2.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lower motor neuron lesions cause flaccid paralysis and muscle wasting at the segmental level of injury.","Damage to anterior horn cells affects only the spinal cord segments at the level of injury.","Central cord syndrome affects both upper and lower motor neurons, with lower motor neuron signs at the level of injury."],"references":["Ameer MA, Tessler J, Munakomi S, Gillis CC. Central Cord Syndrome. 2023 Aug 13. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722961.","Hashmi SZ, Marra A, Jenis LG, Patel AA. Current Concepts: Central Cord Syndrome. Clin Spine Surg. 2018 Dec;31(10):407-412. doi: 10.1097/BSD.0000000000000731. PMID: 30346310.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:22:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:23:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9521"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76656"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{